Hierarchical Clustering¶

  • We will perform the clustering with distance metrics : Euclidean, Manhattan(cityblock), Chebyshev & Mahalanobis.
  • We will perform Clustering with different linkage methods for the above metrics and compares results to choose optimal clusters
In [35]:
# Creating empty list to append the values
corr = []
metric = []
link = []

# list of distance metrics
distance_metrics = ["euclidean", "cityblock"]

# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "weighted"]

for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(df_scaled_subset, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(df_scaled_subset))
        print(
            "Cophenetic correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}.".format(
                dm.capitalize(), lm, c
            )
        )
        corr.append(c)
        metric.append(dm)
        link.append(lm)

Cophenetic correlation for Euclidean distance and single linkage is 0.7391220243806552.
Cophenetic correlation for Euclidean distance and complete linkage is 0.8599730607972423.
Cophenetic correlation for Euclidean distance and average linkage is 0.8977080867389372.
Cophenetic correlation for Euclidean distance and weighted linkage is 0.8861746814895477.
Cophenetic correlation for Cityblock distance and single linkage is 0.7252379350252723.
Cophenetic correlation for Cityblock distance and complete linkage is 0.8731477899179829.
Cophenetic correlation for Cityblock distance and average linkage is 0.896329431104133.
Cophenetic correlation for Cityblock distance and weighted linkage is 0.8825520731498188.

In [37]:
# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "centroid", "ward", "weighted"]

# creating a empty list to store the highest values
high_cophenet_coff = 0
high_lm = [0, 0]

for lm in linkage_methods:
    Z = linkage(df_scaled_subset, metric="euclidean", method=lm)
    c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(df_scaled_subset))
    print("Cophenetic correlation for {} linkage is {}.".format(lm, c))
    if high_cophenet_coff < c:
        high_cophenet_coff = c
        high_lm[0] = "euclidean"
        high_lm[1] = lm

Cophenetic correlation for single linkage is 0.7391220243806552.
Cophenetic correlation for complete linkage is 0.8599730607972423.
Cophenetic correlation for average linkage is 0.8977080867389372.
Cophenetic correlation for centroid linkage is 0.8939385846326323.
Cophenetic correlation for ward linkage is 0.7415156284827493.
Cophenetic correlation for weighted linkage is 0.8861746814895477.

Creating Dendograms for the different linkage methods¶

In [38]:
# to create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

# For each linkage method, we will plot the dendrogram and calculate the cophenetic correlation
for i, lm in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    Z = linkage(df_scaled_subset, metric="euclidean", method=lm)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({lm.capitalize()} Linkage)")

    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(df_scaled_subset))
    axs[i].annotate(
        f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",
        (0.80, 0.80),
        xycoords="axes fraction",
    )

Observations

  • We see from the above diagrams that despite having a high cophenetic correlation, the clustes are not very distinct for Average Linkage.
  • We see that the dendogram for Ward linkage has better and distinct clusters.

Cluster Insights:¶

Cluster 0

  • There are 225 customers in this cluster
  • Average_Credit_Limit for this cluster is low with mean of about \$13000. However, there are two customers who have a high Credit limit of \\$50,000 and \$100,000 respectively.
  • Most customers in this clusters have between 1-3 Total_Credit_Cards.But we see that the upper whisker is at 6. This could correlate to the customers with high credit limits in this cluster.
  • Total_visits_bank is at a lower end between 0-2.
  • Majority of customers have between 3-5 Total_visits_online values, with three outliers in the high end at 10,11 & 12 respectively.
  • Interestingly, Most customers in this cluster have higher Total_calls_made,with values between 5-9.

Cluster 1

  • There are 196 customers in this cluster
  • Average_Credit_Limit is between appros \$13,000 to \\$50,000 for most customers
  • Total_Credit_Cards is moderate at 4-6 cards
  • Most Customers in this cluster have higher bank vists, between 4-5.
  • Total_visits_online is lower
  • Total_calls_made is between 0-3 for most customers

Cluster 2

  • There are only 48 customers in this cluster
  • Avg_Credit_Limit is high for this cluster, with the median at \$150,000
  • Likewise, Total_Credit_Cards is also high.
  • Customers in this clusters have a low Total_visits_bank with median of only 1
  • Total_visits_online is also the highest compared to other clusters
  • Most customers here have Total_calls_made value of only 1.

Cluster 3

  • There are only 14 customers in this cluster
  • The median Avg_Credit_limit is moderate, aroung \$60,000 approx
  • Total_Credit_cards median is at 4
  • Customers in this clusters have made only 2 visits to the bank
  • Total_visits_online is low
  • Total_calls_made is between 0-1 for most customers

Cluster 4

  • There are 177 customers in this cluster
  • The median Avg_Credit_limit is similar to cluster one, at around approx \$30,000
  • The Total_Credit_Cards range is between 5-7 for most customes.
  • Total_visits_bank is moderate, between 2 to 3
  • Total_visits_online is low
  • Total_calls made is between 1-4 for most customers
